  "target_response": {
    "text": "There's an early pattern, but hold it loosely. In 9 tagged late-screen days versus 38 comparison days, your next-day recovery averaged about 3.6 points lower — a small effect, graded low confidence, from a sample I'd still call thin. The bigger problem is entanglement: your late-screen nights are mostly also your late-bedtime nights, so the data can't tell whether the screen, the lost sleep, or whatever kept you up carries the effect. Two ways to sharpen it: keep tagging consistently until the tagged count reaches double digits, and try a handful of nights with screens but an unchanged bedtime. If recovery holds on those nights, it was the hour rather than the screen — which is a genuinely useful thing to know, because it changes the fix from banning the phone to moving the deadline.",
